The morphology and microstructure of the as-prepared N-CQDs/Bi2WO6 hybrid materials were characterized by SEM and TEM analysis. Fig. 4
                        a and b showed the SEM micrographs of the N-CQDs/Bi2WO6 hybrid materials. The hybrid materials are sphere-like structure and the average particle size is in the range of 2–5μm (Fig. 4a). The high-magnification SEM image (Fig. 4b) indicated that the entire sphere-like hierarchical structures consist of numerous nanosheets. Moreover, the nanosheets are intercrossed each other and aggregated together to form sphere-like microspheres. These unique structures may provide more active sites for the adsorption and photocatalysis of organic pollutants. The N-CQDs were difficult to be distinguished by SEM due to their very small size. From the EDS element mapping (Figs. 5 and 6

                        ), the Bi, W, O, C and N elements can be found in the N-CQDs/Bi2WO6-5 hybrid materials.
